  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does a US green card holder need to travel to Canada?",
  "response": "A U.S. green card holder (permanent resident) does not need a visa to travel to Canada for short visits, such as tourism or business, but they must meet certain requirements:\n\n1. **Valid Green Card**: Ensure your green card is valid and not expired.  \n2. **Valid Passport**: You need a valid passport or travel document from your country of citizenship.  \n3. **Electronic Travel Authorization (eTA)**: If you are flying to Canada, you may need to apply for an eTA (Electronic Travel Authorization) before your trip. However, green card holders traveling to Canada by land or sea do not need an eTA.  \n4. **Proof of Status**: Be prepared to show proof of your permanent residency in the U.S. (e.g., your green card).  \n5. **Purpose of Visit**: Be ready to explain the purpose of your visit and provide proof of ties to the U.S. (e.g., return ticket, employment, or residency).  \n\n### Exceptions:\n- If you are from a visa-exempt country, you may not need an eTA, but green card holders from visa-required countries will need one when flying.  \n- If you plan to work, study, or stay in Canada for an extended period, you may need a visa or permit, even as a green card holder.  \n\nAlways check the latest requirements on the official [Government of Canada website](https://www.canada.ca) before your trip.",
